ub. Net evidence count: Bearish has 4+ independent structural supply signals plus a fading geopolitical catalyst with capped upside. Bullish has 2-3 transient demand signals plus short-squeeze optionality. The bear's evidence is of higher quality and more independently corroborated. [Consensus DIVERGENT (Master=BEARISH, Vote=BULLISH) → reduced size]", 'regime': 'HIGH_VOLATILITY', 'volatility_sentiment': 'BULLISH', 'confidence': 0.56, 'price': 3.12, 'sma_200': 3.7094400000000003, 'expected_price': 3.12, 'predicted_return': 0.0, 'thesis_strength': 'PLAUSIBLE', 'conviction_multiplier': 0.7}, {'contract_month': '202606', 'prediction_type': 'DIRECTIONAL', 'direction': 'BEARISH', 'reason': "Evaluating the full body of evidence across eight specialist reports and the debate, the bearish case rests on a stronger and more independent evidentiary foundation than the bullish case, though conviction is moderated by several genuine risks acknowledged by both sides.\n\nON SUPPLY FUNDAMENTALS: The Agronomist, Macro, and Inventory reports converge independently on the same bearish thesis — record dry gas production (112.3 Bcf/d, +7.1% YoY), a 2.5-year high in gas-directed rigs (134 units), storage at essential parity with the five-year average (2,018 Bcf, -7 Bcf), and an incoming demand collapse per LSEG. These are three independent agents reaching the same conclusion for materially different reasons (production data, macro demand forecasting, inventory analysis), which per the evidence-counting rule constitutes a stronger signal than the bullish side's reliance on a single catalyst — the Qatar geopolitical event — viewed through multiple lenses. Regional spot price discounts at Houston Ship Channel ($2.515) and SoCal Border ($1.205) versus Henry Hub confirm there is no physical supply tightness at the hub level.\n\nON THE GLOBAL LNG SHOCK: The Qatar force majeure is real and significant — removing ~20% of global LNG supply is a genuine catalyst. However, the Macro and Geopolitical